<div class="column middle">
  <br><h1>Spiderman: Across the Spideverse</h1>
  <hr style='float: right; width:100%;'><br>
  
  <p>
  A postmodern stylistic masterpiece (or half of one at least). 
  The trouble with multipart movies is that the hype is so high for the second half - if you're gonna end on a cliff hanger, you better have an outstanding resolution. 
  We shall see. 
  But for a first part I can barely fault it, though that doesn't mean it was faultless. 
  For one, I've never been a fan of prophetic vision scenerios in any movie, aka. 'oh no Spot is gonna kill everyone'. 
  This just teases a battle for no other reason than to say: 'bad things are going to happen' *spooky voice*. 
  Whatever. We get it.
  </p>
  <p>
  Other than that, the stylisation worked to tantalising effect, truly differentiating it from any other animation style (even if it was a little bit much at times, like in Gwens universe). 
  My absolute highlight was the direction it took with the plot. 
  Essentially, the Spider universes are supposed to follow 'canon', that is, certain things are supposed to happen. 
  But what if they didn't? 
  Enter Miles Morales. 
  </p>
  <p>
  Spiderman: Into the Spide-verse was basically just an origin story for him, setting the groundwork for this main production. 
  When I describe it as postmodern, what I mean is a playful self-reference, a nuanced balance between fiction and metafiction (and sometimes even metametafiction). 
  By acknowledging and intergrating the 'universal' spiderman story into this one, Spiderman: Across the Spide-verse makes room to play on this. 
  </p>
  <p>
  And play it does.
  </p>
  <p>
  8.6/10
  </p>
  <br>
